No, no, no, no. Did I mention no? I inherited a Javascript application that was maybe 1500 lines of code. Every function was 3-5 lines. Most were like this:<p><pre><code>  process_foos = function(my_list) {
    for (i=0; i<my_list.lengh; i++) {
      process_foo(my_list[i]);
    }
  }
  process_foo = function(foo) {
    foo.some_method();
  }
</code></pre>
And foo.some_method (in another file) was similar.  What it meant was it was <i>impossible</i> to get a view of what was going on in the system. It took months to accomplish an understanding that should have taken weeks.<p>I really think the original authors heard your advice and decided comprehension didn't matter, only function length.<p>Function should accomplish a task. Sometimes (very rarely) a task may be two hundred lines; usually, it is much shorter. Sometimes three lines, but often 15-20.
